                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top of page in brown ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Ottho Kragh</quote>. To the right, in brown ink by a medieval hand: illegible notes. Middle of page: National Library modern exlibris with handwritten signum: <quote>A 42</quote>. Middle of page in black ink by a medieval hand: <quote>beder goth ffor niels oluff son. beder goth ffor ffolmer oll[u]ffson. bedher goth for iøren ollofsson. bedher goth for maren olofs da[tter]. beder got for iakop [?]</quote>. Bottom of page in black ink by a modern hand: <quote>Tillhör Kungliga Bibliotheket i Stockholm. Innehåller 138 blad.</quote>
                                </note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top of page in brown ink by a medieval hand: three circles with signs, Roman numerals and text. Underneath in dark brown ink, by a medieval hand, possibly a mnemonic verse: <quote>Sancte deus bonitas nobis qui semina rerum nasciturum electa qum morbida curia lete accepit rebus iam mensis morte tenebit</quote>. Under this, in dark brown ink by a medieval hand: a text in Danish concerning golden numbers.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Late medieval binding. Brown leather over wooden boards; 4 pairs of raised bands, 2 hook-clasp fastenings. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>: traces of a label with text in brown ink: <quote>35</quote>; stamped in gold: <quote>A 42</quote>; label with text in brown ink: <quote>A 42</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="160" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="110" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="60" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Blind tooling. Double frames; rectangles with motifs inside: flowers along the sides, lozenges at top and bottom. In the centre a medallion with flowers and leaves.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather worn. Leather straps and clasps missing. Spine very worn with significant loss of leather at the top, endbands, the uppermost band and bookblock exposed.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100102">Denmark</placeName>
                                </origPlace>
                                <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1480">15th century, last quarter</origDate>
                            </p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The book originally belonged to one Johanne Nielsdatter, mentioned on <locus from="78v" to="78v" scheme="folios"/>, possibly the daughter of the councillor Niels Christiernsen Munk, see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107247">Nielsen (1956)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="223" to="224" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The Danish nobleman <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102558">Otto Kragh</persName>, whose signature is found on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Kragh's library was taken in the First Northern War <date from="1655" to="1660">(1655–1660)</date>, and some of his books transferred to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName>; see <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107131">Walde (1916–1920)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="2" to="2" unit="volume"/>
                                    <citedRange from="405" to="406" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>. The current signum, <quote>A 42</quote>, was first established in Helin’s catalogue from the 1720s (U 91:2:2). The volume is also mentioned in <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102565">Gustaf Peringer Lillieblad</persName>'s printed catalogue (1706), p. 90: <quote>35. Breviarium Romanum</quote> (signum found on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>From the <orgName>Antiquities Archive</orgName> to the <orgName>National Library</orgName> in <date when="1780"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
